column12: An Improved Indoor Game partaking of the character of both Croquet & Billiards.
column13: 1779. Cole, J. H. Jan. 30. Games imitating croquet and billiards.-A game imitating croquet and billiards is played by means of cues or mallets on a dining or billiard table. When it is played on a dining-table, the table is covered with a cloth, which is kept taut by means of strips l, Fig. 1, of wood forming the boundaries of the table m. These strips are secured to the table by means of wooden clamps k and wedges n, and they are provided with elastic cushions secured by means of rubber solution. , When a billiard table is used, the wooden strips may be used to cover the cushions and pockets of the table. To prevent displacement of the hoops c, Fig. 2, when struck, they are made of a heavy metal; and are cast integral with or leaded into sockets of lead d<1>, the feet of which are covered with rubber or emery or other cloth a. The arches of the hoops are provided with cork cushions d for receiving pins e carrying flags, in order to mark the progress of the game. The pillars, which have to be struck by the balls after passing through the hoops, take the form of a model lighthouse and Irish roundtower, respectively, and each is marked with coloured bands to indicate the order of play. The hoops and pillars are provided with horizontal rings or collars of rubber b, against which the balls can strike and rebound.

A powered seed dispenser for uniformly distributing seeds along the ground which includes a handle carrying a powered driven motor and a pivotally mounted seed distributor which is engaged and driven by the powered driven motor, the seed distributor being constructed of a pair of opposed discs, each disc having a pair of inner and outer sidewalls extending transversely therefrom toward its opposing disc, such discs being constructed and arranged to connect together telescopically in such manner as to create an inner metering chamber and an outer dispensing chamber wherein seeds contained inside the metering chamber discharge through openings in the inner sidewalls from the top portion of the volume of seeds, such seeds then falling into the dispensing chamber defined by the outer sidewalls where they are directed and discharged uniformly through dispensing apertures in the outer sidewalls at a point adjacent to the lowermost point of travel of the dispensing apertures.

A generative sound system has a generative audio engine which is controlled or influenced by the absolute or relative location and/or orientation of a plurality of individual articles or units (71). The articles may, in a variety of embodiments, include collectable cards (86), building blocks (102), articles of furniture, ornaments and so on (128, 130, 132) or portable electronic devices such as mobile phones (60). Position and orientation information may be transmitted by means of a wireless message to the compositional engine, or the engine may determine that information in other ways such as by means of a proximity sensor (124, 136).

column13: The green tire holder disclosed herein comprises a vertical shaft having a plurality of uniformly spaced apart arms extending outwardly therefrom, a slidable shoe mounted on each of said arms for engaging a bead of a green tire and a slidable tread support mechanism mounted on each arm near the outer end thereof. The tire holder includes means for moving all of the shoes simultaneously toward or away from the center by equal amounts, so that the shoes at all times are equidistant from the center. Each tread support mechanism includes, a tiltable support plate, preferably flat, which engages the tread portion of the green tire, and a support arm for supporting the plate. The tread support mechanisms are slidable independently of the shoes. The angle of inclination of the tread support plates may be varied, e.g. from 0.degree. to 60.degree. to the horizontal at 15.degree. intervals.

An improved snow-making nozzle for producing snow from a mixture of compressed air and water comprises a structure permitting less compressed air to be used in producing a moisture laden spray of small uniformly sized aeriated water particles which have sufficient velocity to assure that they freeze in the ambient air before hitting the ground. The invention has internal means defining a longitudinally extending air passageway with a cylindrical end adapted to mate to a source of compressed air and having an adapter portion which alters the cylindrical shape of the passageway to a rectangular cross section of a throat portion having the ratio of the longer side to the shorter side of at least 10 to 1. The top and bottom walls of the throat portion form a convergent-divergent nozzle with the throat portion having an arcuate shape with a radius along the longer rectangular dimension. Nozzle ports are provided at the throat section to inject uniform streams of water into the exiting air, the endmost ports having their axes emanating from approximately the same center as that for the radius of curvature of the throat itself.

Provided herein is an instrument and method useful to incise in to the skin to a precise depth and at a specific angle with respect to the surface of the skin of a patient, for the extraction of individual follicular groups or individual follicular units. An instrument according to the invention precisely limits the depth of incision, and creates a circular incision around a hair, follicular unit, or follicular cluster in a manner such that no damage occurs to any of the hair shafts.

column13: The present invention is a shoe for post operative and rehabilitation use and having a sole (10) with substantially straight longitudinal sides (13) and a longitudinally disposed stiffening member (16). The sole has a rocker that assists the wearer with forward movement when the front portion of the foot is lowered and the heel is raised. The shoe also has an upper member (21, 22) fixed to the sole and adapted to hold the foot in a substantially constant position relative to the shoe. The shoe provides the advantage that the substantially straight longitudinal sides helps prevent inward rotation (pronation) or outward rotation of the foot while walking. Furthermore, the preferred embodiment of the shoe has a shank (16) within the sole to provide a degree of stiffness that prevents movement of the foot in a manner that would aggravate the injury.

column13: A feeder assembly (10) for birds or other animals having a pan member (26), a feeder tube (20) defining a channel (42) for receiving feed from a feed supply and defining a brood gate opening(38), a plurality of wing members (22) having a plurality of fingers (92) for adjustably engaging the feeder tube (20), and a cone member (24) disposed about the feeder tube (20) and slidably mounted to the plurality of wing members (22) by a plurality of engaging arms (110). The cone member (24) is adapted to slide relative to the feeder tube (20) between a raised position to open the brood gate opening (38) and a lowered position to close the brood gate opening (38). The pan member (26) and an end of the cone member (24) define a feed opening (30) for permitting feed to pass from the feeder tube (20) to the pan member (26) for presentation. The feed opening (30) can be adjusted in size either by adjusting the wing members (22) relative to the pan member (26) or by sliding and adjustably positioning the cone member (24) relative to the feeder tube (20) and the wing members (22). The brood gate opening (38) can be opened or closed in an adjustable manner by adjustably positioning the cone member (24) relative to the feeder tube (20) and the wing members (22). The elevation of the brood gate opening (38) can be adjusted by adjusting the wing members (22) relative to the pan member (26). <IMAGE>

column12: Automated foam panel apparatus, blade, and associated method
column13: An apparatus and associated method for constructing prefabricated foam panels is provided. While making a longitudinal pass over a foam block, the apparatus flattens the foam block, cuts longitudinal kerfs in the foam block, and draws metal studs into the kerfs. The apparatus comprises a unique, heated blade having a shape similar to the cross section of a metal stud. The blade kerfs foam blocks, including blocks made of recycled or low-grade foam. The associated method includes kerfing the foam blocks by passing the blade through the foam blocks and drawing metal studs into the kerfs.

column12: IMPROVEMENTS IN OR RELATING TO DIGITAL SIGNAL EQUIPMENT
column13: 1287330 Digital transmission; synchronizing MARCONI CO Ltd 23 April 1971 [9 July 1970] 33299/70 Heading H4P A digital equipment employing a counter 18 as a source on timing pulses has means independent of the counter for continuously monitoring incoming bit signal streams and responsive to a determined number of identifiable bit signal combinations transmitted at the beginning of a stream for resetting the counter in one step to a predetermined count to achieve correct phasing of the counter with respect to the signals. The determined count may be an "all zeroes" condition. Preferably the identifiable combinations are all similar and correspond to a traffic idle signal having the same number of bits as an intelligence character and the means for resetting the counter may comprise a store register having as many stages as bits in one of combinations. A receiver of known type 1 includes main processor 2 receiving clock signals at bit rate from divider 6 also at character rate through a division counter 8; in the embodiment the division ratio n = 10. To synchronize counter 8, received signals are also fed to n = 10 bit register 13 stepping of which is also controlled by divider 6. On receipt of a predetermined bit combination, e.g. a traffic idle signal, detector 14 changes its output to lead 15D and through normally conductive gate 16 to offset three stage counter 17, assumed initially at 00 which gives an output on lead 20 which closes gate 16. Signals on lead 15D also open gate 21 hence signals from division counter 22 move counter 17 forwards. Counter 22 is fed at bit rate through gate 23 also opened when counter 17 is offset. When detector 14 is not detecting a signal, lead 15F is energized hence opens gate 25 hence admitting reverse count signals from counter 22. At full count a signal on lead 26 resets counter 8 to zero. In operation when the first of a plurality of successive idle characters appear in register 13 a signal on line 15D offsets counter 17 which gives a signal on line 20 closing gate 16 and opening gate 23. The signal on lead 15D also opens gate 21. If the next idle signal is detected by 14 at the correct time, gate 21 will pass one forward count to counter 17. If the next idle signal is not detected gate 25 will be open hence counter 17 will receive a reverse count. When counter 17 is full i.e. when the required number of idle characters had been correctly detected, counter 8 is reset in one step to the "all zeroes" condition by a signal over lead 26.

column12: Three Pole Fused Fan And Light Switch
column13: A single phase electrical fitting comprises the electrical elements of a three-pole isolator for fan isolation, a switch in a switched line to activate the room lighting and the fan, and an overcurrent protection device such as a fuse or overload for of both a constant line to the fan and the switched line to both the room light and the fan. column12: Diode pumped, multi axial mode intracavity doubled laser
column13: A diode pumped, multi axial mode, intracavity doubled, intracavity tripled laser, includes at least two resonator mirrors defining a resonator cavity. A laser crystal and a doubling crystal are positioned in the resonator cavity. A tripling crystal is also positioned in the resonator cavity. A diode pump source supplies a pump beam to the laser crystal and produces a laser crystal beam with a plurality of axial modes that are incident on the doubling crystal. This produces a frequency doubled output beam. Further, a diode pumped, multi axial mode, intracavity nonlinearly-converted laser is provided and includes at least two resonator mirrors defining a resonator cavity, a laser crystal and a nonlinear conversion apparatus positioned in the resonator cavity. A nonlinear conversion apparatus is also positioned in the resonator cavity. A diode pump source supplying a pump beam to the laser crystal and produces a laser crystal beam with a plurality of axial modes that are incident on the nonlinear conversion apparatus. The result is a nonlinearly converted output beam that has a % RMS noise of less than 3%

Un composant de structure d'avion comprend un compartiment avant (17) formé d'une cloison avant (19) et d'un revêtement structural (21) placé devant la cloison avant (19) et possédant une surface externe à protéger contre l'accummulation de glace. Le composant comprend également un compartiment arrière (18) délimité par la cloison avant (19) et une cloison arrière (20). Une tuyauterie d'alimentation (25) est placée à l'intérieur du compartiment avant (17) et passe à travers la cloison arrière (18) afin d'y fournir des gaz chauds sous pression dirigés sur la face interne du revêtement structural (21) de façon à empêcher l'accummulation de glace sur la face externe dudit revêtement (21). Une enveloppe de protection (31) entoure la tuyauterie d'alimentation (25), depuis la cloison arrière (20) jusqu'à la cloison avant (19) et délimite ainsi un espace annulaire autour de ladite tuyauterie d'alimentation (25). L'espace annulaire est fermé à son extrémité arrière au niveau de la cloison arrière (20) et sur toute sa longueur située dans le compartiment arrière (18) par l'enveloppe de protection (31) et est ouvert à son extrémité avant de façon à assurer une liaison de circulation gazeuse avec le compartiment avant (17). Ainsi, en cas de fuite de gaz chauds résultants d'une rupture de la tuyauterie d'alimentation (25), les gaz ne peuvent pénétrer dans le compartiment arrière (18) mais passent dans le compartiment avant (17). Un conduit de décharge est prévu pour évacuer vers l'atmosphère les gaz utilisés dans le compartiment avant (17).

column12: PUNCH ASSEMBLY TO FACILITATE HAIR FOLLICLE REMOVAL
column13: Briefly, a punch assembly, such as for removing hair follicles from surrounding tissue, along with methods utilizing the punch assembly, are disclosed. A punch assembly may include a substantially cylindrical body having a proximal end and a distal end, the substantially cylindrical body being formed about a central axis and extending distally from the proximal end. The substantially cylindrical body may include a hair follicle-receiving chamber at least partially defined by an interior wall within the substantially cylindrical body, the interior wall extending distally from the proximal end. The punch assembly may additionally include denticulations arranged at the distal end of the substantially cylindrical body. The denticulations may be beveled in a direction away from the central axis so as to form an outer cutting edge.

column13: A multi-sprocket arrangement for installation on a rear wheel axle of a bicycle includes a sprocket assembly. The sprocket assembly has at least a first sprocket and a second, self-supporting sprocket. The second sprocket is connected to a holding body via the first sprocket by way of a separate, cylindrical fastener which extends parallel to the rear wheel axle. The fastener has a first and a second end which are connected in frictionally fit fashion to drilled holes in the first and second sprockets. The frictionally fit connection between the fastener and the drilled holes of the sprockets prevents an axial movement of the first and second sprockets toward one another. The fastener is additionally connected, at the first and second ends, in form-fitting fashion, to the first and second sprockets such that an axial movement of the first and second sprockets away from one another is also reliably prevented.

column13: 16,329. Kershaw, J., and Cole, J. T. Aug. 1. Dyeing. - Wool, slubbings, yarn, and other fibrous materials are dyed, mordanted, and similarly treated with liquids in a machine which repeatedly compresses or squeezes the material in the vat, when saturated, and allows it to open out after each compression. The material to be treated is placed evenly on a false bottom 2, Fig. 1, preferably made in sections 3, more or less up to a grid or lattice top 90, preferably made in two or more sections 92 and provided with hinged pieces or ends 93 secured to flanges 94 at the sides of the vat 5. The false bottom 2 is raised slowly and lowered rapidly by the action of a driving-shaft 30, journaled on supports 32 and gearing with a longitudinal shaft 20 through mechanism carried by a crossstay 24. This mechanism controls the rotational direction and speed of the shaft 20, which carries worms 17 in gear with right and left handed wormwheels 16 secured to two cross-shafts 10. The shafts 10 have chain-wheels 9 fixed to their ends, one over each corner of the vat 5, and each carrying a chain 8 secured to a vertical rod 7 itself secured to a corner of the false bottom 2. The driving- shaft 30, Figs. 4 and 5, drives the longitudinal shaft 20 through a bevel-gear 36, 37 and a short shaft 35 carrying two loose spur-wheels 38, 39, between which a clutch 40 slides on a feather-key. According to which of these two wheels is engaged by the clutch 40, the longitudinal shaft 20 is driven quickly through the spur-wheel 25 in engagement with the second 39 of the two loose wheels, or slowly in the opposite sense from the first loose wheel 38 through change-wheels 41, 45. The clutch 40 is thrown into gear with either of its coacting wheels 38, 39 by the fall of a weighted lever 50, the lower end 53 of which has a slot 54 through which passes a pin 55 secured to a forked or rounded piece 56, fitting a recess 57 in the clutch and capable of sliding on a short shaft 58. Through a slot 60 in the upper arm of the lever 50 passes a rod 61, having an adjustable collar 62, 63 on each side of the lever and its ends fastened to the ends of a chain 64 passing over a sprocket-wheel 65 on the nearer cross-shaft 10 and over a guide-wheel 66. When either collar contacts with the lever, it throws the lever over from one side to the other. Mechanism for allowing the false bottom 2 to dwell at the bottom of the vat 5 comprises a vertical rod 68 adjustably secured to an horizontal plate 69 pivoted at 70<a> to a bracket 70, itself secured to a vertically-sliding feathered rod 71. The clutch 40 carries a collar 80, which when the clutch is thrown out of gear with the quick-drive loose spur-wheels 39, contacts with the vertical rod 68. This forces the other end 72 of the plate 69, suitably shaped for the purpose, into contact with a constantly rotating buttress thread 73, against the tension of a spring 81. Accordingly the buttress thread raises the bracket 70 and other parts attached thereto, including the vertical rod 68, until the lower end of the latter is lifted out of the way of the collar 80, whereupon the clutch 40 is thrown into gear with the slow-drive loose spur-wheel 38, the false bottom 2 being thus slowly raised. During this motion the vertical rod 68 rests on the periphery of the collar 80, and falls again when the clutch is again thrown into gear with the quick-motion spur-wheel 39, a counterweight and the necessary fittings being provided to prevent sho:k.

column13: A UNIQUE FEEDER (10) FOR BIRDS AND ANIMALS OF THE TYPE FORMING PART OF A MODERN AUTOMATED FEEDING SYSTEM (12) USED TO MINIMIZE THE OPERATING COSTS ASSOCIATED WITH COMMERCIAL BREEDING. THE FEEDER ASSEMBLY (10) COMPRISES FEEDER TUBE MEANS (32), A PAN MEMBER (38) AND MAY INCLUDE CONE MEANS (34) LOOSELY SURROUNDING THE FEEDER TUBE (32) FOR CONTROLLING THE PATTERN AND AMOUNT OF FEED PRESENTED IN THE PAN (38). INDEXING MEANS (75) AND VISUAL INDICATION (55) MAY ALSO BE PROVIDED FOR ENABLING THE PRESELECTION OF THE SIZE OF A LOWER FEED GATE (62) WHICH AUTOMATICALLY RESULTS WHEN THE FEEDER (10) IS SUSPENDED ABOVE A FEEDING SURFACE (30) AND PROVIDING CONSTANT INDICATION OF THE SIZE SELECTED, RESPECTIVELY. A BROOD GATE (60) MAY ALSO BE PROVIDED WHICH IS DESIGNED TO AUTOMATICALLY CLOSE UPON ELEVATION OF THE FEEDER (10) ABOVE A FEEDING SURFACE (30), BUT WHICH CAN ALSO BE LOCKED OPEN WHEN SO DESIRED. MOREOVER, THE FEEDER (10) IS PREFERABLY PROVIDED WITH A HANGER MEANS (102, 104,106) TO ENABLE SIMULTANEOUS SUSPENSION OF THE PAN (38) FROM THE BARRIER MEANS (36) UPON DISENGAGEMENT THEREFROM. column13: A unique feeder (10) for birds and animals of the type forming part of a modern automated feeding system (12) used to minimize the operating costs associated with commercial breeding. The feeder assembly (10) comprises feeder tube means (32), a pan member (38) and may include cone means (34) loosely surrounding the feeder tube (32) for controlling the pattern and amount of feed presented in the pan (38). Indexing means (75) and visual indication means (55) may also be provided for enabling the preselection of the size of a lower feed gate (62) which automatically results when the feeder (10) is suspended above a feeding surface (30) and providing constant indication of the size selected, respectively. A brood gate (60) may also be provided which is designed to automatically close upon elevation of the feeder (10) above a feeding surface (30), but which can also be locked open when so desired. The unique feeder (10) may also include rotatable coupling means (84) to engage and disengage the pan member (38) and a barrier means (36) by simply rotating one with respect to the other. The barrier means (36) is designed to facilitate the egress of birds or animals which might otherwise be trapped inside the feeder (10) and make ingress more difficult than egress. Moreover, the feeder (10) is preferably provided with a hanger means (102, 104, 106) to enable simultaneous suspension of the pan (38) from the barrier means (36) upon disengagement therefrom.

column13: An aircraft structural component e.g. an engine nacelle nose cowl, comprises a forward compartment (17) formed by a forward bulkhead (19) and a skin structure (21) which has an outer surface to be protected from accumulation of ice and a rear compartment (18) formed between the forward bulkhead (19) and a rear bulkhead (20). A supply duct (25) extends through rear compartment (18) and into forward compartment (17) for the delivery of pressurised hot gases to the inner surface of the skin structure (21). A protective shroud duct (31) surrounds the supply duct (25) between rear bulkhead (20) and forward bulkhead (19) and forms an annular space around the supply duct (25). The annular space is closed at the rear bulkhead (20) and throughout its length within rear compartment (18) by shroud duct (31) and is open at its forward end into the forward compartment (17), whereby leakage of hot gases from the supply duct (25) upon rupture are prevented by the shroud duct (31) from entering into rear compartment (18). A discharge duct (45) (Figs 2 - 3) is provided for discharging spent gases from the forward compartment (17) to atmosphere. <IMAGE>

column13: A multi-sprocket arrangement for installation on a rear wheel axle of a bicycle includes a sprocket assembly. The sprocket assembly has at least a first sprocket and a second, self-supporting sprocket. The second sprocket is connected to a holding body via the first sprocket by way of a separate, cylindrical fastener which extends parallel to the rear wheel axle. The fastener has a first and a second end which are connected in frictionally fit fashion to drilled holes in the first and second sprockets. The frictionally fit connection between the fastener and the drilled holes of the sprockets prevents an axial movement of the first and second sprockets toward one another. The fastener is additionally connected, at the first and second ends, in form-fitting fashion, to the first and second sprockets such that an axial movement of the first and second sprockets away from one another is also reliably prevented.

EN ENSAMBLAJE ALIMENTADOR (10) COMPRENDE UN TUBO DE ALIMENTACION (32), UNA FUENTE DE ALIMENTACION (38) Y PUEDE INCLUIR UN CONO RODEANDO EL TUBO DE ALIMENTACION (32), PARA CONTROLAR LA CADENCIA Y CANTIDAD DE PASO DEL PIENSO PRESENTE EN EL COMEDERO (38). MEDIOS DE INDEXACION (75) E INDICACION VISUAL (55) TAMBIEN PUEDEN ESTAR PRESENTES PARA PERMITIR LA PRESELECCION DE TAMAÑOS Y UNA PUERTA INFERIOR DE ALIMENTACION (62) QUE SE CIERRA AUTOMATICAMENTE CUANDO EL ALIMENTADOR ESTA SUSPENDIDO POR ENCIMA DE LA SUPERFICIE DE ALIMENTACION (30) Y QUE SUMINISTRA UNA INDICACION CONSTANTE DEL TAMAÑO SELECCIONADO. SE PUEDE INCORPORAR UNA PUERTA (60) TIPO CLUECA (60) QUE ESTA DISEÑADA PARA CERRARSE AUTOMATICAMENTE DESPUES DE LA ELEVACION DEL ALIMENTADOR (6), POR ENCIMA DE LA SUPERFICIE DE ALIMENTACION (30), PERO QUE PUEDE TAMBIEN MANTENERSE CERRADA CUANDO SE DESEE. EL ALIMENTADOR UNICO PUEDE TAMBIEN INCLUIR ELEMENTOS DE ACOPLAMIENTO GIRATORIO (84) PARA ACOPLAR Y DESACOPLAR LOS ELEMENTOS DEL COMEDERO (38) Y A LOS ELEMENTOS DE BARRERA (36) MEDIANTE LA SIMPLE ROTACION DE LOS ELEMENTOS ENTRE SI. LOS ELEMENTOS DE BARRERA (36) ESTAN DISEÑADOS PARA FACILITAR LA SALIDA DE LAS AVES O ANIMALES QUE PUEDAN QUEDAR ATRAPADOS EN EL INTERIOR DEL ALIMENTADOR (10) Y HACER LA ENTRADA MAS DIFICIL QUE LA SALIDA. ADEMAS, EL ALIMENTADOR (10) ESTA DOTADO DE ELEMENTOS DE COLGAMIENTO (102, 104, 106) PARA PERMITIR LA SUSPENSION SIMULTANEA DEL COMEDERO (38) DE LOS ELEMENTOS DE BARRERA (36).

column12: Improvements in or relating to the manufacture of knitted hose
column13: 1,129,983. Knitting machines. KLINGER MFG. CO. Ltd. 25 Oct., 1965, No. 45043/65. Heading D1C. An out-turned welt is knitted on a circular machine in a manner similar to that described in specification 1084281 by providing sinkers with an upper 99 and lower 98 loop drawing edge, Figure 7, such that the initial set up courses F, are knitted and drawn over the upper edge 99, Figure 8, and subsequently the sinkers and needles are manipulated to enable the loops on alternate needles to be held on their stems, Figure 10, in the throats 96 of the sinkers whilst all of the needles continue to knit at the upper edge level of the sinkers to produce ,the welt. Simultaneously with the knitting of the welt an air blast is directed downwardly close to the inside of the needle circle where knitting occurs to exert draw off tension on the fabric when knitting takes place. To complete the turned welt the sinkers are withdrawn to permit the needles to draw loops over the lower edge of the sinkers through the last course of 'the welt and the loops held on the stems of The alternate needles so that these latter loops are knitted into the fabric. Knitting is then continued by drawing loops over the lower edge of the sinkers. To enable the sinkers to be withdrawn and inserted to position the loops on the stems of the alternate needles and to enable knitting to be carried out at both upper and lower edge levels of the sinkers, adjustable sinker cams 55, 60, Figure 4, not shown, are provided and are operated as required from the cam drum of the machine. Simultaneously to alter the draw of the needles to correspond to the loop drawing edges of the sinkers the stitch cams 37, 38 Fig. 3, not shown, are vertically adjustably controlled by linkwork from the cam drum. After the production of the set up courses and when the loops have been drawn down by the alternate needles to engage them in the throats 96 of the sinkers a movable central lifting cam 47 raises the alternate needles to ensure that they take yarn into their hooks without knitting it. Subsequently all of the needles take yarn and knit for the completion of the welt.

A glass refinishing apparatus is disclosed in which a hydraulically driven buffer is slidably and pivotally guided over the exterior surface of an automobile windshield to produce a smooth and polished finish thereon. The buffer is rotatably mounted on a motor housing that is adapted to be manipulated manually. The motor housing is slidably mounted on a pair of guide rods to enable the buffer to axially traverse along the lengths thereof. The bases of the guide rods are connected to a support arm which in turn is pivotally mounted on a fulcrum. In one embodiment, the fulcrum is adapted to be mounted on the studs located on the automobile which normally support the windshield wipers. This construction enables the buffer to traverse the windshield in an arc similar to the traversal of the windshield wiper. In a second embodiment, the fulcrum is adapted to be mounted on a pair of suction cups in order to be universally mounted on or near any glass surface.

An aircraft structural component comprises a forward compartment (17) formed by a forward bulkhead (19) and a skin structure (21) which extends forwardly of the forward bulkhead (17) and which has an outer surface which requires to be protected from accumulation of ice thereon, and a rear compartment (18) formed between the forward bulkhead (19) and a rear bulkhead (20). A supply duct (25) extends through the rear compartment (18) and into the forward compartment (17) for the delivery thereto of pressurised hot gases for distribution over the inner surface of the skin structure (21) to prevent accumulation of ice on the outer surface of the skin structure (21). A protective shroud duct (31) surrounds the supply duct (25), extends from the rear bulkhead (20) to the forward bulkhead (19) and forms an annular space between the protective shroud duct (31) and the supply duct (25). The annular space is closed off at its rear end at the rear bulkhead (20) and throughout its length within the rear compartment (18) by the protective shroud duct (31) and is open at its forward end to provide gaseous flow communication with the forward compartment (17), whereby leakage of hot gases from the supply duct (25) upon rupture are prevented by the protective shroud duct (31) from entering into the rear compartment (18) and pass into the forward compartment (17). A discharge duct is provided for discharging spent gases from the forward compartment (17) to atmosphere.

column12: LONG DISTANCE SHOOTING TOOL FOR TARGET IDENTIFICATION, COMMUNICATION, AND BALLISTIC DATA
column13: Provided is a tool for providing long distance shooters with the ability to receive information from others in the field to adjust their weapon system for the best advantage based on distance, location, and range. The tool may implemented as an application on a mobile device such as a smart phone, for example, making the tool light weight, space efficient, and portable for use in the field. The communication ability allows for tracking shooting partners as well as on-the-spot coordination. The tool further provides range markings, yard lines, and topographic data that allow the shooter to make decisions based on real time data. Shooters are therefore afforded a tool that is portable, easy to use, and flexible enough to use in high-pressure environments.

column12: Improvements in or relating to circular knitting machines
column13: Float or tuck stitch patterning is achieved on a circular machine having welt mechanism by providing frangible tooth butt jacks 23, Fig. 5, not shown, beneath the nucleus and a hump cam 46 Fig. 7, not shown which is slidably positioned to engage the lower end of each jack and project it outwardly so that its lowermost butt 25, Fig. 9, not shown, is positioned in the path of raising cams 51, 52, 53, 54 Fig. 4, not shown. Prior to the jacks being raised by the cam 54 selectors, pivotally mounted and actuated by a pattern drum, selectively depress some of the jacks to prevent their butts 25 engaging cam 54 thereby preventing selection of the compounding needles. The selectors may be further actuated in groups by control levers when it is desired to knit a continuous overall pattern.

column13: 122,227. Kershaw, J., and Cole, J. T. Jan. 5, 1918. Passing fluids through materials.-A dyeing or like apparatus of the kind described in Specification 16329/08, wherein material is alternately compressed and allowed to expand between a movable perforated bottom and a fixed lattice top, is provided with a circulating pump arrangement for passing liquid through the material in either direction, a spraying-device, modified means for operating the movable bottom, means for raising the lattice top, and an attachment for treating materials in hank form. A spraying-device comprising horizontal pipes 16 and a perforated shallow tank is arranged above the lattice top 10 of the vat, and is supplied with liquid from a telescopic pipe 18 connected to a circulating system through a three-way valve 29. The circulating system comprises a pump 22 communicating on its suction side with the bottom of the tank through pipes 23, 24, a three-way valve 25 being interposed in the pipe 23 with a side pipe 26 connecting to a storage tank. A pipe 21a from the outlet of the pump connects to the spraying-device through the valve 29, at which is a connexion 28 to the upper side of the storage tank. A pipe 30 extends from a three-way valve 27 to the pipe 23, and a pipe 35 with a valve 36 from a three-way valve 37 in the pipe 23 to the pipe 21<a>. Side pipes 31 connected to the tank at 33 are connected to the pipe 35. By regulating the various valves, liquid may be circulated through the tanks in different manners without reversing the pump. The bottom grid 4 is supported by a frame 6, which is lifted by chains &c. 9 connected to drums 53<a> on a shaft 53, which is driven so as to raise and lower the grid alternately. The mechanism for producing this effect comprises a driven cross shaft 40 rotated by two sets of fast and loose pulleys 44, 45, which are driven at different speeds and in different directions by belts moved on to their respectively pulleys by slides 44<a> and 45<a> mounted on a slide 46. The slide 46 is operated by a lever 47 pivoted thereto and mounted on a rocking shaft 48, which is provided with a hand-lever 51, by the movement of which either of the fast pulleys 44, 45 may be connected to the power source, the belt of the other set of pulleys running on a loose pulley. In a central position of the lever defined by a locking- pin engaging a hole 52, both sets of gearing will be engaged with loose pulleys. The shaft 40 drives the shaft 53 by pinions 61, 60 and worm gearing 58, 55. A chain 66 runs over a pulley 63 on the shaft 53 and a guide-pulley 64, and serves for automatically reversing the motion of the grid 4. A lever 67 is mounted on the rocking shaft 48 and is connected to a slotted link 70 pivoted to an arm 71 of a three-armed lever mounted on a shaft 72, the other arms of which are provided with a tumbler weight 74 and a balance weight 76 respectively. A hand-lever 77 is mounted on the shaft 72 having a projecting fork 78, which embraces the chain 66 and is engaged by stops 80 thereon to throw the levers 71. 47 from one side to the other as the chain moves up or down and thereby reverse the motion of the grid 4. The lattice top 10 is raised by chains &c. 87 passing over pulleys 88 and wound on a ratchet-controlled shaft 85. Means for supporting material in hank form consists of end plates 90 secured to the top and having slots 91 for receiving hank-supporting laths.

A unique feeder (10) for birds and animals of the type forming part of a modern automated feeding system (12) used to minimize the operating costs associated with commercial breeding. The feeder assembly (10) comprises feeder tube means (32), a pan member (38) and may include cone means (34) loosely surrounding the feeder tube (32) for controlling the pattern and amount of feed presented in the pan (38). Indexing means (75) and visual indication means (55) may also be provided for enabling the preselection of the size of a lower feed gate (62) which automatically results when the feeder (10) is suspended above a feeding surface (30) and providing constant indication of the size selected, respectively. A brood gate (60) may also be provided which is designed to automatically close upon elevation of the feeder (10) above a feeding surface (30), but which can also be locked open when so desired. The unique feeder (10) may also include rotatable coupling means (84) to engage and disengage the pan member (38) and a barrier means (36) by simply rotating one with respect to the other. The barrier means (36) is designed to facilitate the egress of birds or animals which might otherwise be trapped inside the feeder (10) and make ingress more difficult than egress. Moreover, the feeder (10) is preferably provided with a hanger means (102, 104, 106) to enable simultaneous suspension of the pan (38) from the barrier means (36) upon disengagement therefrom.

Hydride compounds with silicon and germanium core atoms and method of synthesizing same
column13: A method is provided for synthesizing silicon-germanium hydride compounds of the formula (H 3 Ge) 4-x SiH x , wherein x=0, 1, 2 or 3. The method includes combining a silane triflate with a compound having a GeH 3 ligand under conditions whereby the silicon-germanium hydride is formed. The compound having the GeH 3 ligand is selected from the group consisting of KGeH 3 , NaGeH 3 and MR 3 GeH 3 , wherein M is a Group IV element and R is an organic ligand. The silane triflate can be H x Si(OSO 2 CF 3 ) 4-x or H x Si(OSO 2 C 4 F 9 ) 4-x . The method can be used to synthesize trisilane, (H 3 Si) 2 SiH 2 , and the iso-tetrasilane analog, (H 3 Si) 3 SiH, by combining a silane triflate with a compound comprising a SiH 3 ligand under conditions whereby the silicon hydride is formed. The silane triflate can include H x Si(OSO 2 CF 3 ) 4-x or H x Si(OSO 2 C 4 F 9 ) 4-x wherein x=1 or 2. A method for synthesizing (H 3 Ge) 2 SiH 2 includes combining H 3 GeSiH 2 (OSO 2 CF 3 ) with KGeH 3 under conditions whereby (H 3 Ge) 2 SiH 2 is formed.

column13: 756,841. Stockings. COLE, J. M. R. REYMES-. Aug. 7, 1953 [May 7, 1952; June 12, 1953], Nos. 11480/52 and 16234/53. Drawings to Specification. Class 141. [Also in Group VIII] The heel of a stocking is formed by continuous rotary knitting on a circular knitting machine, using a thermoplastic yarn such as nylon, the heel then being stretched on a form and submitted to heat so that it assumes the desired shape in which it sets upon the fabric cooling. Some shaping is achieved in the knitting of the heel by periodically removing the instep needles from operation and by varying the loop length in the heel portion. If desired, only the heel part is knitted of thermoplastic yarn, the foot and leg being knitted of natural or artificial silk or lisle. Specification 756,861 is referred to.

column12: Improvements in the toes of stockings and the like and a method and machine for producing them
column13: 727,394. Knitting. KENDALL CO. Dec. 31, 1951 [Nov. 6, 1950], No. 27009/50. Class 74 (2). To produce a stocking toe in knitting from the toe upwards on a circular machine, initially inactive spaced toe fashioning needles, over at least one arc 16 of the circle, are progressively introduced at each side of a medial point in the arc, during circular knitting, to begin new wales. Surplus fabric 14 is then trimmed away and the edges joined by linking or seaming. As shown, equally-spaced (e.g. alternate) needles and sinkers throughout the entire circle are inactive during the knitting of a few courses 11. A small group of such needles in those instep needles which knit the centre of the toe are then introduced, with their sinkers. Thereafter, at intervals of a few courses, further pairs of groups are introduced, one on each side of the activated needles until all fashioning needles 16 are knitting. Rows of fashioning holes T<SP>1</SP>, T<SP>2</SP>, T<SP>3</SP>, T<SP>4</SP>, T<SP>5</SP> are thus produced. The toe may be of a comparatively stout thread or of real or artificial silk or nylon plus a splicing thread. Loop size may be evened up as in Specification 723,301. Toe fashioning needles may be introduced over two opposed arcs, corresponding to foot top and bottom, surplus fabric being cut-away at the sides. The foot may be fashioned by needles devoted to that purpose. The heel is produced by rotary knitting, heel fashioning needles and their sinkers being periodically introduced starting from the outer or inner ends of the group 18, 18<SP>1</SP> thereof, to produce upwardly-convergent or divergent lines 25 of fashioning holes; in the latter case, a splicing thread, fed to needles producing the foot bottom, may be fed to the heel needles, so that at the heel the edges of the spliced areas coincide with the fashioning line whilst, above the heel, the splicing thread may be continued to form a high splice. The heel pouch may be accentuated by periodically restraining the instep needles from knitting during one revolution, the yarn floats being subsequently cut out, or eliminated by trapping and cutting mechanism as in Specifications 532,520, 532,586 or 570,810. The heel may be knitted by reciprocation, in the normal manner. The leg is fashioned by progressive introduction of leg fashioning needles 19, 19<SP>1</SP> and their sinkers, the introduction beginning at either end of the groups, to produce upwardly convergent or divergent lines 22 of fashioning holes. The thigh may be fashioned, immediately below the welt, by progressive introduction of groups 20, 201 of fashioning needles. If desired, all sinkers may be active at the beginning of the toe, the resulting visual contrast between the two qualities of fabric thus produced being eliminated before production of that part of the stocking leg normally above the shoe (e.g. at the start of the heel) by withdrawing from activity the sinkers associated with the leg fashioning needles and introducing them as the associated needles are introduced.

column12: HYDRIDE COMPOUND WITH SILICON AND GERMANIUM CORE ATOM AND METHOD FOR SYNTHESIZING SAME
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a method for synthesizing silicon-germanium hydride compounds of the formula (HGe)SiH, wherein x=0, 1, 2 or 3.SOLUTION: The method includes combining a silane triflate with a compound having a GeHligand under conditions whereby the silicon-germanium hydride is formed. The compound having the GeHligand is selected from the group consisting of KGeH, NaGeHand MRGeH, wherein M is a group IV element and R is an organic ligand. The silane triflate can be HSi(OSOCF)or HSi(OSOCF). The method can be used to synthesize trisilane: (HSi)SiH, and the iso-tetrasilane analog: (HSi)SiH, by combining a silane triflate with a compound comprising a SiHligand under conditions whereby the silicon hydride is formed. The silane triflate can include HSi(OSOCF)or HSi(OSOCF)wherein x=1 or 2. A method for synthesizing (HGe)SiHincludes combining HGeSiH(OSOCF) with KGeHunder conditions whereby (HGe)SiHis formed.

column12: SYSTEMS AND METHODS FOR MEDICAL PROCEDURE CONFIRMATION
column13: A method comprises advancing a surgical instrument toward a target tissue. The surgical instrument includes a marker that is deposited at a location at or near the target tissue. After depositing the marker, the surgical instrument is withdrawn away from the target tissue. After withdrawing the surgical instrument, the location of the deposited marker is used to determine a trajectory of a distal end of the surgical instrument at or near the target tissue.

column12: Diode pumped,multiaxial mode intracavity doubled laser
column13: A diode pumped, multiaxial mode, intracavity frequency doubled laser resonator has high amplitude stability, meaning that the percent root mean square noise (% RMS) of the doubled output beam power is low. A diode pump source supplies a pump beam to a laser crystal (Nd:YVO4) positioned in a resonator cavity and produces a multiaxial mode infrared beam that is incident on a doubling crystal (KTP), also positioned in the resonator. A frequency doubled output beam is produced that has an RMS of less than 3 %, and in some cases less than 0.2 %. The laser is highly efficient, provides high output power, and its output beam is of high spatial quality.

column12: DIODE PUMPED MULTIAXIAL MODE INTRACAVITY FREQUENCY DOUBLED LASER
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a continuous-wave (CW), diode-pumped, multiaxial mode, intracavity-frequency-doubled solid-state laser with high amplitude stability.

SOLUTION: The diode pumped, intracavity nonlinearly-converted laser comprises at least two resonator mirrors that defines a resonator cavity having a length longer than 30 cm, and an optical axis. It also comprises a laser crystal positioned in a resonator cavity, a nonlinear conversion device positioned in the resonator cavity, a diode pump source for supplying a pump beam with a %RMS noise of less than 3% to the laser crystal, and a power supply apparatus for supplying power to the diode pump source. The pump beam to the laser crystal preferably has a plurality of axis modes. Furthermore, the laser preferably operates in TEMOOmode.

The body armor assembly includes a backing plate formed of a metal or a metal alloy with randomly oriented atoms, or fibers that have a random orientation. column12: A METHOD AND SYSTEM FOR MEASURING A VERTICAL DENSITY PROFILE OF A FLUID
column13:
In a method and system for measuring a vertical density profile of a fluid (2) in a fluid storage tank (1) an array of open-ended pressure pipes (4) extends downward into said fluid. The top end of each pressure pipe is connectable with a common pressurizing gas supply (9) and the bottom end incorporates a fluid level sensor head (3). The following steps are carried out for each pipe: 
- connecting said pipe with the common gas supply, 
- conducting the pressurizing gas into said pipe thereby forcing the fluid downward into said fluid level sensor head, comprising a lower end part in which the fluid passes an outlet opening forming an abrupt transition between said lower end part and an open ended tube, 
- determining a level indicating signal from the passing fluid, 
- determining a pressure indicating signal from the pressure on the fluid, and 
- deriving from said level and pressure indicating signals information on the said vertical density profile.

column12: Sanitizing package-ready pre-quantified units of food
column13: A method and apparatus for reducing pathogens in successive pre-measured units of a flowable food product without substantially increasing the head height requirement of a feed production system. A plurality of containers are moved about a path within a housing. The path has a plurality of stations, such as a receiving station, one or more sanitizing stations, and a dispensing station, and a container cleaning station. A pre-measured unit of the flowable food product is received at the receiving station into a container. The pre-measured unit of the flowable food product is exposed to one or more sanitizing agents at one or more sanitizing stations. The pre-measured unit of the flowable food product is dispensed into the packaging device at the dispensing station. The containers are then cleaned at the container cleaning station to prepare each container to receive a subsequent pre-quantified unit of the flowable feed product.

Improved methods of placing a gravel pack in a wellbore and in one or more perforations extending from the wellbore into a producing zone are provided. The methods basically comprise the steps of placing a screen in the wellbore adjacent the perforations, and then injecting a low viscosity carrier liquid having a particulate solid pack material suspended therein into the space between the screen and the walls of the wellbore containing the perforations. The pack material has a specific gravity substantially the same as the specific gravity of the carrier liquid whereby a low viscosity carrier liquid can be utilized and the carrier liquid-pack material suspension contains a high loading of pack material.

column12: Diode pumped, multi axial mode intracavity doubled laser
column13: A diode pumped, multi axial mode, intracavity doubled, intracavity tripled laser, includes at least two resonator mirrors defining a resonator cavity. A laser crystal and a doubling crystal are positioned in the resonator cavity. A tripling crystal is also positioned in the resonator cavity. A diode pump source supplies a pump beam to the laser crystal and produces a laser crystal beam with a plurality of axial modes that are incident on the doubling crystal. This produces a frequency doubled output beam. Further, a diode pumped, multi axial mode, intracavity nonlinearly-converted laser is provided and includes at least two resonator mirrors defining a resonator cavity, a laser crystal and a nonlinear conversion apparatus positioned in the resonator cavity. A nonlinear conversion apparatus is also positioned in the resonator cavity. A diode pump source supplying a pump beam to the laser crystal and produces a laser crystal beam with a plurality of axial modes that are incident on the nonlinear conversion apparatus. The result is a nonlinearly converted output beam that has a % RMS noise of less than 3%

column12: System and Method for Governing Data Entry Into a Network Data Base by Multiple Entities Having Varying Data Requirements
column13: A system for governing entry of data into a database commonly accessible by a plurality of entities, each of which has requirements for its data that differ from the requirements of other entities, comprised one or more rules base servers for storing a rules base data structure. The data structure is a collection of documents which are either a rule applicable to an entity or a rules interface which provides a navigation route to an applicable rule. The system includes a rules engine which executes an algorithm that recursively searches the documents in the rules base, evaluating each document until a rule is found, executing the rule, and storing the result returned by the executed rule, until all applicable rules for the entity submitting the set of data are executed.

column12: ACTIVE SUSPENSION SYSTEM FOR VEHICLE SEAT
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To actively move a vehicle seat in a plurality of directions in response to a vehicle movement by controlling a seat operating member in response to feedbacks of a plurality of sensors monitoring movements of a vehicle and the seat operating member and limiting seat movements for the ground. SOLUTION: A suspension system is provided with hydraulic cylinders C1 to C6 moving a seat and an electronic control module(ECM) is connected with valve assemblies V1 to V6 , a position sensor 23, a linear variable displacement transducer monitoring movements of a vehicle and a vehicle seat and a triaxial accelerometer 35. When the vehicle receives shock, the linear variable displacement transducer and the triaxial accelerometer 35 impart feedbacks to the ECM the ECM transmits ECM electronic control singnals to the valve assemblies V1 to V6 , the hydraulic cylinders C1 to C6 are operated, movements of the vehicle seat for shock is limited or removed, and a driver is prevented from sensing shock.

column12: Method for circumferential dimension measuring and control in crystal rod pulling
column13: The circumference of a crystal rod is monitored and controlled during the rod growing process by providing relative rotation between the growing crystal rod and a melt of the crystal material as the rod is being pulled from the melt according to the Czochralski method, and by using a radiation-sensitive control system for adjusting growth conditions of the rod in response to variations in a radiation signal which is indicative of the circumferential dimension of the rod. An electronic circuit integrates the radiation signal over each complete rotation of the rod, thereby eliminating unnecessary adjustment of the growth conditions in response to diametric variations of the rod which recur regularly in each rotation.

column12: Hydride compounds with silicon and germanium core atoms and method of synthesizing same
column13: A method is provided for synthesizing silicon-germanium hydride compounds of the formula (H 3 Ge) 4-X SiH X , wherein x=0, 1, 2 or 3. The method includes combining a silane triflate with a compound having a GeH 3 ligand under conditions whereby the silicon-germanium hydride is formed. The compound having the GeH 3 ligand is selected from the group consisting of KGeH 3 , NaGeH 3 and MR 3 GeH 3 , wherein M is a Group IV element and R is an organic ligand. The silane triflate can be H X Si(OSO 2 CF 3 ) 4-x or H x Si(OSO 2 C 4 F 9 ) 4-x . The method can be used to synthesize trisilane, (H 3 Si) 2 SiH 2 , and the iso-tetrasilane analog, (H 3 Si) 3 SiH, by combining a silane triflate with a compound comprising a SiH 3 ligand under conditions whereby the silicon hydride is formed. The silane triflate can include H X Si(OSO 2 CF 3 ) 4-x or H X Si(OSO 2 C 4 F 9 ) 4-x wherein x=1 or 2. A method for synthesizing (H 3 Ge) 2 SiH 2 includes combining H 3 GeSiH 2 (OSO 2 CF 3 ) with KGeH 3 under conditions whereby (H 3 Ge) 2 SiH 2 is formed.

column13: A method is provided for synthesizing silicon-germanium hydride compounds of the formula (H 3 Ge) 4-x SiH x , wherein x=0, 1, 2 or 3. The method includes combining a silane triflate with a compound having a GeH 3 ligand under conditions whereby the silicon-germanium hydride is formed. The compound having the GeH 3 ligand is selected from the group consisting of KGeH 3 , NaGeH 3 and MR 3 GeH 3 , wherein M is a Group IV element and R is an organic ligand. The silane triflate can be H x Si(OSO 2 CF 3 ) 4-x or H x Si(OSO 2 C 4 F 9 ) 4-x . The method can be used to synthesize trisilane, (H 3 Si) 2 SiH 2 , and the iso-tetrasilane analog, (H 3 Si) 3 SiH, by combining a silane triflate with a compound comprising a SiH 3 ligand under conditions whereby the silicon hydride is formed. The silane triflate can include H x Si(OSO 2 CF 3 ) 4-x or H x Si(OSO 2 C 4 F 9 ) 4-x wherein x=1 or 2. A method for synthesizing (H 3 Ge) 2 SiH 2 includes combining H 3 GeSiH 2 (OSO 2 CF 3 ) with KGeH 3 under conditions whereby (H 3 Ge) 2 SiH 2 is formed.

column12: DIODE PUMPED, MULTIAXIAL MODE INTRACAVITY DOUBLED LASER
column13: A diode pumped, multiaxial mode, intracavity frequency doubled laser resonator has high amplitude stability, meaning that the percent root mean square noise (% RMS) of the doubled output beam power is low. A diode pump source supplies a pump beam to a laser crystal (Nd:YVO4) positioned in a resonator cavity and produces a multiaxial mode infrared beam that is incident on a doubling crystal (KTP), also positioned in the resonator. A frequency doubled output beam is produced that has an RMS of less than 3 %, and in some cases less than 0.2 %. The laser is highly efficient, provides high output power, and its ouput beam is of high spatial quality.

A milling cutter is provided including a tool holder and a cutting tool insert. The tool holder includes a mounting end portion and a cutting end portion. T he cutting end portion includes a slot defined by first and second diagonal surfaces provided in an end of the cutting end portion. The first and second diagonal surfaces form a substantially V-shaped pocket for receiving the cutting tool insert. The cutting tool insert includes a substantially flat body member having a V-shaped seat portion and a cutting portion, the cutting portion includes a first cutting lobe and a second cutting lobe. A hole is provided which passes through the body member. A scr ew hole passes through the cutting end portion of the milling cutter which intersects the U-shaped pocket. A threaded portion of the screw hole is offset from a clearance portion of the screw hole to positively seat the V-shaped seat portion of th e insert in the V-shaped pocket of the tool holder.

1,047,303. Charging batteries from variablespeed generators. J. STONE & CO. (DEPTFORD) Ltd. June 17, 1965 [June 19, 1964], No. 25539/64. Heading H2H. Battery-charging apparatus of the kind in which a battery 5 is charged by an A.C. generator 1 driven by a prime mover which can run at different speeds selectable by the main contacts (not shown) of a relay 9 comprises auxiliary contacts 10 on the relay which are operated such as to insert the resistance 11 into circuit when a high prime mover speed, and hence high generator voltage, is chosen so as to maintain the voltage applied to the battery approximately the same as that when a low prime mover speed is selected. Alternatively the battery voltage may be maintained by using the contacts 10 to control the saturation of a saturable reactor inserted into the circuit between the alternator 1 and the rectifier 6. The alternator may have a permanent magnet excitation and the system may be three phase.

column12: A method of and apparatus for generating colour matte signals.
column13: A method of generating colour matte signals comprises the steps of: inputting hue, saturation, and luminance values; calculating R, G and B colour component values from the hue, saturation and luminance values; calculating luminance (Y), and colour difference component (Cr and Cb) values from the calculated R, G and B values; and outputting the calculated Y, Cr, and Cb values. The hue value in two parts, the first of which defines one of six segments formed by dividing each side of the colour triangle in half and the second of which define intermediate values within the segment. The R, G and B values are determined by calculating three colour components from the saturation, luminance and the second part of the hue value, and assigning the three colour components to registers for holding R, G and B values in dependence on the segment defined by the first of the hue value.

column12: METHOD, APPARATUS AND SALT FOR DESCALING METAL STRIP
column13: A method, apparatus and salt for descaling a strip (15) of metal includes a nozzle assembly (45) mounted within a spray box (25) for spraying descaling product on the strip. The nozzle assembly (45) includes a spray chamber (52); nozzles (60, 66) mounted directly to the spray chamber; and a heater (87) for heating the chamber, the descaling product in the chamber, and the nozzles by conduction through the chamber. The nozzles are oriented to direct the descaling product in a spray against the upper and lower surfaces of the metal strip (15) for an amount and a time sufficient to descale the metal strip (15). The nozzle assembly (45) is attached to the spray box (25) and can be easily removed therefrom for inspection.

1,126,432. Flame-proofing. PROBAN Ltd. 3 Aug., 1967 [3 May, 1966], No. 19572/66. Heading DIP. A flame-proof fabric comprising modacrylic and cellulosic fibres is produced by treating the cellulosic fibres or the fabric with a precondensate formed from urea and a methylol and/or aziridinyl phosphorus compound and then effecting curing. The modacrylic fibres comprise 35-85% of acrylonitrile and 15- 65% of vinyl or vinylidine chloride. The cellulosic fibres may be of cotton, flax, jute, aminised cellulose, or regenerated cellulose. The methylol phosphorus compound may be THPC or THPO. The aziridinyl phosphorus compound may be APO or APS. Curing may to effected by treatment with gaseous followed by aqueous ammonia.

column12: METODO Y APARATO PARA DESINCRUSTAR UNA TIRA METALICA.
column13: Un sistema para desincrustar una tira de metal que incluye un ensamble de tobera montado dentro de una caja de rocío para rociar el producto desincrustante sobre la tira. El conjunto de tobera incluye una cámara de rocío. Toberas montadas directamente a la cámara de rocío; y un calentador para calentar la cámara, el producto desincrustante en la cámara y las toberas por conducción a través de la cámara, las toberas están orientadas para dirigir el producto desincrustante en un chorro contra las superficies superior e inferior de la tira metálica en una cantidad y tiempo suficientes para desincrustar la tira metálica. El ensamble de tobera está unido a la caja de rocío y fácilmente puede retirarse del mismo para su inspección.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR INVESTIGATING A NON-PLANAR SAMPLE
column13: Method and apparatus for investigating a sample particularly a pharmaceutical tablet. An emitter and/or the sample are initially positioned so that the emitter is at a predetermined distance and normal angle to a first point on a surface of the sample. The emitter then irradiates the sample with radiation having a plurality of frequencies in the range from 25GHz to 100THz at a plurality of points on the surface of the sample. Relative motion is possible between the emitter and the sample so that the surface of the sample can be tracked to maintain the predetermined distance and normal angle at each of the plurality of points, and allow radiation transmitted and/or reflected from the sample at the plurality of points to be detected. This has particular application to imaging the structure or composition of a coating on a pharmaceutical tablet.

column12: METHOD OF AND APPARATUS FOR DIGITAL DATA STORAGE
column13: Digital data storage conventionally requires an election to be made between retaining data on-line, which consumes expensive media, or moving it to a far cheaper archive medium, which is relatively inaccessible. This specification discloses a hybrid arrangement in which all material is retained on-line, but is progressively degraded as it becomes less useful, with off-line storage of the source material. A milling cutter is provided including a tool holder and a cutting tool insert. The tool holder includes a mounting end portion and a cutting end portion. The cutting end portion includes a slot defined by first and second diagonal surfaces provided in an end of the cutting end portion. The first and second diagonal surfaces form a substantially V-shaped pocket for receiving the cutting tool insert. The cutting tool insert includes a substantially flat body member having a V-shaped seat portion and a cutting portion, the cutting portion includes a first cutting lobe and a second cutting lobe. A hole is provided which passes through the body member. A screw hole passes through the cutting end portion of the milling cutter which intersects the U-shaped pocket. A threaded portion of the screw hole is offset from a clearance portion of the screw hole to positively seat the V-shaped seat portion of the insert in the V-shaped pocket of the tool holder.

column12: SANITIZING PACKAGE-READY PRE-QUANTIFIED UNITS OF FOOD
column13: A method and apparatus for reducing pathogens in successive pre-measured units of a flowable food product without substantially increasing the head height requirement of a feed production system. A plurality of containers are moved about a path within a housing. The path has a plurality of stations, such as a receiving station, one or more sanitizing stations, and a dispensing station, and a container cleaning station. A pre-measured unit of the flowable food product is received at the receiving station into a container. The pre-measured unit of the flowable food product is exposed to one or more sanitizing agents at one or more sanitizing stations. The pre-measured unit of the flowable food product is dispensed into the packaging device at the dispensing station. The containers are then cleaned at the container cleaning station to prepare each container to receive a subsequent pre-quantified unit of the flowable feed product.

column13: An environment is monitored, for example for pollution, by detecting changes in the movements of plant materials or animals which are very small, i.e. no larger than 3000 mu m. These materials and animals include, for example, algae, protozoa, microorganisms, insects, pollen, spores and seeds. The environment is normally gaseous or aqueous. In one arrangement, a vessel V contains the plant material or animals, and their movements are detected by use of a light beam L from a source C, to display a speckle pattern on a screen S, the speckle pattern being inspected and measured to obtain movement information. Alternatively, the light beam L can be combined with a reference beam to give an interference pattern containing doppler frequencies indicative of organism movement. <IMAGE>

column12: PROCESS FOR THE PURIFICATION OF ALUMINIUM CHLORIDE
column13: 1,270,126. Purification of aluminium chloride. BRITISH TITAN Ltd. 4 March, 1970 [29 March, 1969], No. 16602/69. Heading C1A. Impure aluminium chloride is treated to reduce the amount of metallic impurities by feeding it to a molten mixture of a salt of an alkali metal and aluminium chloride at a temperature below the sublimation temperature of pure aluminium chloride and in the presence of a metal more electropositive than iron but not more electropositive than aluminium and contacting the mixture with a carrier gas to remove the purified aluminium chloride. The metal is preferably in powder form and is preferably aluminium but may also be titanium, zirconium or zinc. The purification process may be continuous and more than one addition of metal may be made. The alkali metal salt may be a halide, preferably a chloride and more than one alkali metal salt may be present. The carrier gas may be air, oxygen, inert gas or vaporized titanium chloride.

A scaffold wall system for erecting temporary insulated facilities using a scaffold structure for support is disclosed. The system comprises a floor supported by the scaffold structure, a plurality of walls supported by the floor, and a ceiling supported by the walls. The floor comprises a plurality of support beams laid across the scaffold structure, and floor boards laid across the support beams. The walls comprise a plurality of wall panels placed into customized tracks secured to the floor. Insulative sleeves are placed between the wall panels. The ceiling also comprises a plurality of panels with insulative sleeves. The system allows for multiple levels of temporary insulated facilities to be erected within a scaffold.

column12: A METHOD AND SYSTEM FOR MEASURING A VERTICAL DENSILY PROFILE OF A FLUID
column13: In a method and system for measuring a vertical density profile of a fluid in a fluid storage tank an array of open-ended pressure pipes extends downward into said fluid. The top end of each pressure pipe is connectable with a common pressurizing gas supply and the bottom end incorporates a fluid level sensor head. The following steps are carried out for each pipe: - connecting said pipe with the common gas supply, - conducting the pressurizing gas into said pipe thereby forcing the fluid downward into said fluid level sensor head, comprising a lower end part in which the fluid passes an outlet opening forming an abrupt transition between said lower end part and an open ended tube, - determining a level indicating signal from the passing fluid, - determining a pressure indicating signal from the pressure on the fluid, and - deriving from said level and pressure indicating signals information on the said vertical density profile.

column13: Embodiments of collapsible wheels and methods of making collapsible wheels are generally described herein. The collapsible wheels can each comprise a plurality of wheel sections, a plurality of rims, and spokes connecting the plurality of wheel sections to the plurality of rim portions. The plurality of rim portions are positioned along a perimeter of a circle that defines a central plane of the wheel. Each wheel section supports one or more spokes that connect to one or more of the rim portions. The wheel sections are rotatable relative to each other around an axis from a collapsed configuration to an expanded position. Other embodiments may be described and claimed.

column12: Improvements in or relating to glass fiber optical systems
column13: <PICT:1048855/C1/1> In the manufacture of fused glass fibre optical devices having a multiplicity of individually insulated light conducting channels extending end-to-end, a plurality 21 of relatively rigid but resilient glass clad glass rods 22 are supported in spaced side-by-side relation, as between the wires 26 of woven wire screens 24, 25, or perforations 29 in a plate 28 (Fig. 10, not shown), and are then pressed endwise into intimate side-by-side relation to a heating zone 54 where they are fused together. The rod assembly 21 is secured above one screen 24 by a resin 32 to an adaptor 30 with a reduced part 34 held in an arm 43 extending from a slide 40 mounted for vertical movement on a pair of columns 36, 37 (Fig. 4, not shown) and operated by a lead-screw 46 engaging a threaded lug 47 thereon. The heating zone 54 is fixedly mounted on an arm 53 on a platform 52 clamped to the columns 36, 37 and comprises an annular electrical heating element 62 aligned with the adapter 30 and opening 65 in arm 53. The second screen 25 rests on a spacer 68 and a die 66, of carbon to prevent sticking, having a tapered central opening 67, the lower end of which is substantially the same shape as the rod assembly 21 and of a size to just take the rods 22 in intimate side-by-side relation as they are pressed down by rotation of lead-screw 46. The heated and fused rod assembly 21 is then drawn out to a multifibre bundle 23 by means of a rotatable drum 70 operated from the same motor 50 as the lead-screw 46 by means of suitable gearing 49.

column13: In a body armor assembly and method of forming the body armor assembly a strike plate is provided that is formed of a number of sheets layered on each other. Each sheet of the strike plate is formed of fibers having a parallel orientation greater than 70%. The sheets are oriented such that the parallel-oriented fibers of all of the plural sheets are oriented or aligned in a single direction. The body armor assembly includes a backing plate formed of a metal or a metal alloy with randomly oriented atoms, or fibers that have a random orientation. The backing plate and the strike plate are joined, or bonded, or cross-linked together. Each strike plate sheet can be formed of ultra-high-molecular-weight polyethylene (UHMWPE) fibers. The backing plate can be formed of polyethylene thermoplastic fibers.

column12: Sanitizing Package-Ready Pre-Quantified Units of Food
column13: A method and apparatus for reducing pathogens in successive pre-measured units of a flowable food product without substantially increasing the head height requirement of a feed production system. A plurality of containers are moved about a path within a housing. The path has a plurality of stations, such as a receiving station, one or more sanitizing stations, and a dispensing station, and a container cleaning station. A pre-measured unit of the flowable food product is received at the receiving station into a container. The pre-measured unit of the flowable food product is exposed to one or more sanitizing agents at one or more sanitizing stations. The pre-measured unit of the flowable food product is dispensed into the packaging device at the dispensing station. The containers are then cleaned at the container cleaning station to prepare each container to receive a subsequent pre-quantified unit of the flowable feed product.

Circumferential error signal apparatus for crystal rod pulling
column13: The circumference of a crystal rod is monitored and controlled during the rod growing process by providing relative rotation between the growing crystal rod and a melt of the crystal material as the rod is being pulled from the melt according to the Czochralski method, and by using a radiation-sensitive control system for adjusting growth conditions of the rod in response to variations in a radiation signal which is indicative of the circumferential dimension of the rod. An electronic circuit integrates the radiation signal over each complete rotation of the rod, thereby eliminating unnecessary adjustment of the growth conditions in response to diametric variations of the rod which recur regularly in each rotation.

column12: Improvements relating to electrical supply systems
column13: 938,302. Supply systems for railway vehicle services. J. STONE & CO. (DEPTFORD) Ltd. May 9, 1962 [July 18, 1961], No. 26047/61. Class 38 (4). An electrical supply system comprising a variable-speed alternator has the excitation of the alternator so arranged that the current delivered by the alternator remains substantially constant over a wide range of speed. The alternator 3 is provided with main and auxiliary field windings 4, 5 wound in an additive sense, the main winding 4 being excited in accordance with the load 1 on the alternator, the auxiliary winding 5 being excited in inverse proportion to the output frequency of the alternator by way of a frequency-sensitive circuit 6, the choke 9 of which saturates at high frequencies. The excitation of the auxiliary winding 5 is thus greater at low frequencies so that the full output of the alternator 3 is developed at very low speeds. The alternator is preferably a high-frequency unsaturated machine. The system may incorporate a variable resistor whereby the output level of the alternator may be adjusted.

column12: Artificial intelligence (AI) language detection and translation system for scanning radio signals and rules-based transmission of alerts
column13: Apparatus and associated methods relate to a system including a portable hardware device having a radio antenna, the device being operably coupled to a network, where the device includes electronics for scanning ambient radio messages using the antenna, evaluating a message for sentiment (e.g., intent-to-harm) using at least one artificial intelligence technique, and upon determining the presence of intent-to-harm, transmitting an alert signal over the network to a target entity as determined by a set of alert transmission rules based at least in part on the content/context/metadata of the message. In an illustrative example, a portable pack may be preconfigured with automatic language translation and speech detection capabilities. The pack may scan ambient radio signals for specific words/phrases of interest (W/POI). Upon detecting dangerous/aggressive sentiment, an alert may be relayed to a higher command, advantageously providing decision-makers with invaluable, real-time intelligence to adapt to fast-changing developments on the battlefield.
